&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>$ convert -append figP*.png out.png
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>when I got error stating that &lt;code>cache resources exhausted&lt;/code>. I was first surprised because it was the same set of images I combined a couple of days before EXCEPT that I significantly increased their resolution. So I googled the error message and found &lt;a href="https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/issues/396">this issue&lt;/a> on the GitHub repository of ImageMagick.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Well, turns out it was not a issue at all, I simply needed to change the memory limit as explained &lt;a href="https://www.imagemagick.org/script/security-policy.php">here&lt;/a> and well summarized in the issue:&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>